Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Scholarly Communications &amp; Copyright Librarian Abbotsford , BC Description Job Summary: The University of the Fraser Valley (UFV) Library is a hub at the university for students, faculty, and staff. Reporting to the University Librarian, the successful candidate will be responsible for delivering a university-wide copyright education program and developing scholarly communications initiatives suitable for the UFV research environment. The Scholarly Communications &amp; Copyright Librarian is also responsible for supporting open education initiatives at UFV. In performing their duties, the Scholarly Communications &amp; Copyright Librarian will liaise with other UFV librarians, faculty, staff, and administrators, as well as the Teaching and Learning department, the bookstore, print services, the Office of Research and Graduate Studies, and legal counsel. The incumbent is also expected to maintain copyright expertise through professional development activities and external communication with counterparts at other Canadian universities, affiliated associations, and other professional groups or organizations. The Scholarly Communications &amp; Copyright Librarian is part of a team providing high level of research assistance to students, faculty, and staff across multiple disciplines. The successful candidate will also teach library instruction classes across a wide range of disciplines and, as a liaison librarian, will work closely with assigned departments and their teaching faculty. This position is based on the Abbotsford campus but will require travel to other UFV campuses; the incumbent must have their own transportation.Qualifications:Master of Library and Information Studies (or equivalent) from an American Libraries Association accredited institution.Academic or professional library background is required with a minimum of two years of experience.Formal education or demonstrated expertise in Canadian copyright law, including familiarity with Indigenous matters involving intellectual property, and experience with current practices in copyright management is essential.Knowledge of copyright compliance guidelines and database licensing in a post-secondary educational environment and a demonstrated ability to assist faculty and staff with copyright and licensing queries for teaching and research needs is essential.Experience in providing assistance and consultation to academic researchers and faculty on scholarly communication issues, including publishing, author rights, research metrics, open access, Creative Commons licensing, and other aspects of research outputs and dissemination.Experience with the development and delivery of open education support resources and services, and readiness to conduct related advocacy and outreach activities directed at faculty, staff, and students.Experience and ability to plan and deliver instructional sessions. Reference experience via in-person, phone, email, online chat, and other communication channels.Excellent written and oral communication skills, and strong management and organizational skills.Ability to work both independently and collaboratively in a team environment.Ability to recognize, respect, and work effectively with individuals and groups with diverse perspectives and backgrounds is required. Demonstrated knowledge of issues related to equity, diversity, inclusivity, Indigenization, decolonization, and accessibility.A second degree in a related field such as law, education, or publishing is considered an asset.Experience as an academic liaison librarian to academic programs is considered an asset.Familiarity with Libguides and other Springshare products, Askaway, and experience with institutional repository management, particularly Islandora, is considered an asset.Working knowledge of client-side web technologies such as HTML, Javascript and CSS and/or server-side programming languages such as PHP and Python is considered an asset.How to Apply:See the full posting @: https://ufv.njoyn.com/CL3/in/share/JobDetails.asp?clid=56144&amp;jobid=J0724-1302&amp;BRID=282875&amp;LANG=1&amp;SBDID=1
About UFVThe University of the Fraser Valley is located on the traditional territory of the Halq'eméylem-speaking peoples. We express our gratitude and respect for the honour of living and working in Stó:lo Tém:éxw (Stó:lo Land; Stó:lo World). In all that we do, UFV strives to support and honour the Stó:lo peoples goals of self-determination and well-being on these lands. A commitment to Indigenization and Reconciliation is core to our institutional Vision and Integrated Strategic Plan: IYAQAWTXW — which means House of Transformation. This commitment includes the goal of centering Indigenous ways of knowing throughout our organization, recognizing our responsibilities to community, and a multi-year plan to increase the number of Indigenous faculty, staff, and administrators working at UFV.UFV has four campus locations within the beautiful Fraser Valley in British Columbia. Recognized as one of BC's top employers, UFV offers a combination of career and lifestyle benefits. Join a team of 1,400 passionate professionals who value integrity, inclusivity and excellence. At UFV, you will serve a vibrant community, and shape the future of 15,000 students.Indigenization, equity, and diversity are essential to our work as a university. A diverse community fosters the inclusion of voices that have been historically underrepresented and marginalized. At UFV, we are committed to recruiting a diverse workforce that represents the community we proudly serve. We encourage applications from Indigenous peoples, members of groups that experience discrimination due to race, colour, place of origin, ancestry, and/or religion, persons who identify as women and 2SLGBTQ+, and persons with disabilities. We invite applicants to complete a confidential self-identification survey as part of the application process. All questions are voluntary, with an option to decline to answer. Information will be used to support efforts to broaden the diversity of the recruitment process, and results are not shared with the selection committee. Inquiries about the survey may be directed to careers@ufv.ca. Learn more about our commitment to diversity and inclusion.All qualified candidates are encouraged to apply; however, Canadians and permanent residents will be given priority. In an effort to be both environmentally and fiscally responsible, UFV will contact only candidates receiving an interview. We thank all applicants for considering UFV for employment. Shortlisted applicants may be required to undergo a criminal record check and/ or a verification of their education credentials. UFV is committed to the principle of equity in employment. Compensation 70,437.00 - 112,872.00 per year Closes: 31 August, 2024 University of the Fraser Valley Abbotsford , BC Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
